#MEM id=lean-startup source=/root/yvon/agent-department/COO/diana/skills/marketplace/lean-startup/SKILL.md
M|lean-startup|name: lean-startup
M|lean-startup|description: 'Design MVPs, validated learning experiments, and pivot-or-persevere decisions using Build-Measure-Learn. Use when the user mentions "MVP scope", "validated learning", "pivot or persevere
M|lean-startup|license: MIT
M|lean-startup|metadata:
M|lean-startup|author: wondelai
M|lean-startup|version: "1.1.0"
M|lean-startup|A systematic approach to building startups and launching new products that shortens dev cycles and rapidly discovers if a business model is viable.
M|lean-startup|**Entrepreneurship is a form of management.** Success doesn't require a perfect plan or brilliant insight—it requires a systematic process for testing assumptions, learning from customers, and iterati
M|lean-startup|**The foundation:** Most startups fail not because they couldn't build what they planned, but because they built the wrong thing. The Lean Startup methodology applies scientific experimentation to eli
M|lean-startup|**Goal: 10/10.** When reviewing or creating product dev plans, experiments, or metrics, rate them 0-10 based on adherence to Lean Startup principles. A 10/10 means full application of Build-Measure-Le
M|lean-startup|The fundamental cycle of Lean Startup:
M|lean-startup|```
M|lean-startup|IDEAS
M|lean-startup|↓
M|lean-startup|BUILD → Product
M|lean-startup|↓
M|lean-startup|MEASURE → Data
M|lean-startup|↓
M|lean-startup|LEARN → knw
M|lean-startup|↓
M|lean-startup|(back to IDEAS)
M|lean-startup|```
M|lean-startup|**Critical insight:** The loop is actually backward. Start with what you want to learn, determine metrics that will inform that learning, then build the minimum product to collect those metrics.
M|lean-startup|**Reverse planning:**
M|lean-startup|1. **What do we want to learn?** (hypothesis to test)
M|lean-startup|2. **How will we know if we learned it?** (metrics)
M|lean-startup|3. **What's the minimum we can build?** (MVP)
M|lean-startup|**Goal:** Minimize total time through the loop.
M|lean-startup|See: [references/build-measure-learn.md](references/build-measure-learn.md) for detailed loop execution.
M|lean-startup|**Definition:** Learning what customers really want through validated experiments, not opinion or anecdotes.
M|lean-startup|**Validated learning is not:**
M|lean-startup|- Building features customers request (they don't know what they want)
M|lean-startup|- Achieving vanity metrics (downloads, signups without engagement)
M|lean-startup|- Doing surveys or focus groups (people lie/mispredict behavior)
M|lean-startup|**Validated learning is:**
M|lean-startup|- Testing hypotheses with real behavior
M|lean-startup|- Measuring what customers *do*, not what they *say*
M|lean-startup|- Running experiments that could falsify your assumptions
M|lean-startup|- Learning = when your predictions were wrong
M|lean-startup|**The Validation Ladder:**
M|lean-startup|| Level | Evidence | Strength |
M|lean-startup||-------|----------|----------|
M|lean-startup|| 1 | "I think customers want this" | Weakest (opinion) |
M|lean-startup|| 2 | "Customers said they want this" | Weak (stated preference) |
M|lean-startup|| 3 | "Customers signed up for early access" | Medium (low commitment) |
M|lean-startup|| 4 | "Customers paid a deposit" | Strong (real commitment) |
M|lean-startup|| 5 | "Customers are actively using it" | Strongest (revealed preference) |
M|lean-startup|**Target:** Level 4-5 before building at scale.
M|lean-startup|**Definition:** The version of a new product that allows a team to collect the maximum amount of validated learning with the least effort.
M|lean-startup|**MVP is not:**
M|lean-startup|- A prototype (not about proving tec feasibility)
M|lean-startup|- A beta version (not about quality or features)
M|lean-startup|- A minimum marketable product (it might be embarrassing)
M|lean-startup|**MVP is:**
M|lean-startup|- A learning vehicle
M|lean-startup|- The smallest experiment to test a hypothesis
M|lean-startup|- Often much smaller than you think
M|lean-startup|**MVP Types:**
M|lean-startup|| Type | What It Is | When to Use | Example |
M|lean-startup||------|------------|-------------|---------|
M|lean-startup|| **Concierge** | Manual service pretending to be automated | Test if solution is valuable | Food on the Table (manual meal planning) |
M|lean-startup|| **Wizard of Oz** | Fake automation, manual backend | Test if automation is needed | Zappos (no inventory, bought shoes retail) |
M|lean-startup|| **Smoke test** | Landing page + signup, no product | Test demand before building | Dropbox video (explained concept, measured signups) |
M|lean-startup|| **Single feature** | One core feature only | Test which feature is most valuable | Twitter (just status updates) |
M|lean-startup|| **Piecemeal** | Combine existing tools | Test workflow before custom build | Groupon (WordPress + email) |
M|lean-startup|**MVP Design Questions:**
M|lean-startup|- What's the riskiest assumption to test first?
M|lean-startup|- What's the minimum to test that assumption?
M|lean-startup|- How do we measure if the assumption was validated?
M|lean-startup|**Common mistakes:**
M|lean-startup|- Building too much (overestimate MVP size)
M|lean-startup|- Optimizing for scale prematurely
M|lean-startup|- Confusing quality with learning (MVP can be low quality)
M|lean-startup|- Skipping the experiment (building without hypothesis)
M|lean-startup|See: [references/mvp-design.md](references/mvp-design.md) for MVP types and design patterns.
M|lean-startup|**Definition:** The assumptions that, if wrong, will cause your business to fail.
M|lean-startup|**Process:**
M|lean-startup|1. **Identify your business model's critical assumptions**
M|lean-startup|2. **Prioritize by risk** (which failure would be fatal?)
M|lean-startup|3. **Test the riskiest assumption first**
M|lean-startup|**Common leap-of-faith assumptions:**
M|lean-startup|| Assumption Type | Question | Test Method |
M|lean-startup||----------------|----------|-------------|
M|lean-startup|| **Value hypothesis** | Do customers care about this problem? | Smoke test, concierge MVP |
M|lean-startup|| **Growth hypothesis** | How will customers discover us? | Channel tests, referral experiments |
M|lean-startup|| **Retention hypothesis** | Will customers come back? | Cohort analysis, engagement metrics |
M|lean-startup|| **Monetization hypothesis** | Will customers pay? | Pre-orders, pricing tests |
M|lean-startup|**Example: Dropbox**
M|lean-startup|- **Leap-of-faith:** "People will download and use a file sync tool"
M|lean-startup|- **Test:** Explainer video showing product (before building full version)
M|lean-startup|- **Metric:** Beta signup list grew from 5,000 to 75,000 overnight
M|lean-startup|- **Learning:** Validated demand before building scale infrastructure
M|lean-startup|**Anti-pattern:** Testing assumptions in order of ease rather than risk.
M|lean-startup|See: [references/assumptions.md](references/assumptions.md) for assumption mapping frameworks.
M|lean-startup|**Definition:** Measuring progress when traditional accounting doesn't apply.
M|lean-startup|**The problem with traditional metrics:**
M|lean-startup|- Revenue (startups start at $0)
M|lean-startup|- Customers (startups start at 0)
M|lean-startup|- Vanity metrics (look good but don't drive decisions)
M|lean-startup|**Innovation accounting framework:**
M|lean-startup|**Question:** Where are we today?
M|lean-startup|Measure current reality, even if it's zero or embarrassing.
M|lean-startup|**Metrics to establish:**
M|lean-startup|- Conversion funnel (signup → active → retained → paying)
M|lean-startup|- Engagement (DAU/MAU, ses length, features used)
M|lean-startup|- Economics (CAC, LTV, churn rate)
M|lean-startup|**Goal:** Know your starting point precisely.
M|lean-startup|**Question:** What can we improve to move toward our goal?
M|lean-startup|Run experiments to improve baseline metrics.
M|lean-startup|**Examples:**
M|lean-startup|- A/B test pricing ($9/mo vs. $19/mo)
M|lean-startup|- Test onboarding flows (% who complete setup)
M|lean-startup|- Experiment with channels (SEO vs. paid vs. referral)
M|lean-startup|**Goal:** Systematically improve metrics through validated learning.
M|lean-startup|**Question:** Are we making sufficient progress, or do we need to change str?
M|lean-startup|Based on data, decide whether to continue or pivot.
M|lean-startup|**Criteria:**
M|lean-startup|- Are metrics moving in the right direction?
M|lean-startup|- Is the rate of improvement acceptable?
M|lean-startup|- Are we learning what we expected?
M|lean-startup|**Goal:** Make evidence-based strategic decisions.
M|lean-startup|See: [references/innovation-accounting.md](references/innovation-accounting.md) for metric frameworks and dashboards.
M|lean-startup|**Vanity metrics:** Make you feel good but don't change behavior.
M|lean-startup|**Actionable metrics:** Drive decisions and clarify cause and effect.
M|lean-startup|| Vanity | Why It's Bad | Actionable Alternative |
M|lean-startup||--------|-------------|------------------------|
M|lean-startup|| **Total signups** | Always goes up, no ctx | **% signup → active** (conversion rate) |
M|lean-startup|| **Page views** | Doesn't indicate value | **Time on page**, **bounce rate** |
M|lean-startup|| **Total users** | Includes inactive/churned | **Active users** (DAU, WAU, MAU) |
M|lean-startup|| **Downloads** | Doesn't mean usage | **DAU/downloads** (activation rate) |
M|lean-startup|| **Revenue** | Without ctx | **Revenue per cohort**, **LTV/CAC** |
M|lean-startup|**Three characteristics of actionable metrics:**
M|lean-startup|1. **Actionable:** Clear cause-and-effect (can reproduce)
M|lean-startup|2. **Accessible:** Simple, understandable by everyone
M|lean-startup|3. **Auditable:** Can check the underlying data (not a black box)
M|lean-startup|**Example:**
M|lean-startup|- **Vanity:** "We have 100,000 users!"
M|lean-startup|- **Actionable:** "Users from channel X have 2x retention vs. channel Y. Let's double down on X."
M|lean-startup|**Cohort analysis:** Group users by signup date and track behavior over time. Reveals if product is actually improving.
M|lean-startup|See: [references/metrics.md](references/metrics.md) for metric selection and tracking.
M|lean-startup|**Pivot:** A structured course correction designed to test a new hypothesis about the product, str, or engine of growth.
M|lean-startup|**When to pivot:**
M|lean-startup|- Experiments consistently fail to validate hypotheses
M|lean-startup|- Metrics are flat despite multiple iterations
M|lean-startup|- Customer feedback contradicts your vision
M|lean-startup|- Progress is too slow given runway
M|lean-startup|**When to persevere:**
M|lean-startup|- Metrics are improving (even if slowly)
M|lean-startup|- Clear learning is happening
M|lean-startup|- Adjustments are moving in right direction
M|lean-startup|**Pivot Types:**
M|lean-startup|| Pivot Type | What Changes | Example |
M|lean-startup||------------|-------------|---------|
M|lean-startup|| **Zoom-in pivot** | Single feature becomes the whole product | Instagram (photo filters from Burbn check-in app) |
M|lean-startup|| **Zoom-out pivot** | Product becomes a single feature | Flickr (photo-sharing from Game Neverending) |
M|lean-startup|| **Customer segment** | Same problem, different customer | Groupon (activism platform → local deals) |
M|lean-startup|| **Customer need** | Same customer, different problem | Potbelly Sandwich (antique store → sandwiches) |
M|lean-startup|| **Platform** | App → Platform or Platform → App | YouTube (dating site → video platform) |
M|lean-startup|| **Business architecture** | High margin, low volume ↔ Low margin, high volume | Salesforce (software → SaaS) |
M|lean-startup|| **Value capture** | Monetization model change | Android (paid → free + app revenue) |
M|lean-startup|| **Engine of growth** | Viral, sticky, or paid growth model | Facebook (viral within colleges → paid advertising) |
M|lean-startup|| **Channel** | How you reach customers | Salesforce (direct sales → self-service) |
M|lean-startup|| **Technology** | Different technology, same solution | Apple (Intel → ARM chips) |
M|lean-startup|**Pivot cadence:** Many successful startups pivot 1-5 times before finding product-market fit.
M|lean-startup|**Anti-pattern:** "Pivot" without validating that the new direction solves the core problem.
M|lean-startup|See: [references/pivots.md](references/pivots.md) for pivot dec frameworks and case studies.
M|lean-startup|**Growth engine:** How your startup acquires and retains customers sustainably.
M|lean-startup|**Choose one engine to focus on:**
M|lean-startup|**Mechanism:** High retention, low churn
M|lean-startup|**Formula:** `Growth rate = New customer acquisition rate - Churn rate`
M|lean-startup|**Focus:** Keep customers coming back
M|lean-startup|**Metrics:**
M|lean-startup|- Churn rate (% who stop using per month)
M|lean-startup|- Retention cohorts (% still active after 30/60/90 days)
M|lean-startup|- Engagement (DAU/MAU ratio)
M|lean-startup|**Examples:** SaaS, subscription services, soc networks
M|lean-startup|**str:** Improve product until churn rate is low enough that natural growth exceeds churn.
M|lean-startup|**Mechanism:** Customers bring other customers
M|lean-startup|**Formula:** `Viral coefficient = (% who invite) × (invites sent) × (% who join)`
M|lean-startup|**Focus:** Viral coefficient > 1.0 = exponential growth
M|lean-startup|**Metrics:**
M|lean-startup|- Viral coefficient (invites → signups)
M|lean-startup|- Viral cycle time (how long until referred user invites others)
M|lean-startup|- Referral source attribution
M|lean-startup|**Examples:** Dropbox, Hotmail, WhatsApp
M|lean-startup|**str:** Build virality into the product. Must be > 1.0 to be self-sustaining.
M|lean-startup|**Mechanism:** Spend money to acquire customers
M|lean-startup|**Formula:** `LTV (Lifetime Value) > CAC (Customer Acquisition Cost)`
M|lean-startup|**Focus:** Unit economics that allow reinvestment
M|lean-startup|**Metrics:**
M|lean-startup|- CAC (cost per acquisition)
M|lean-startup|- LTV (average revenue per customer)
M|lean-startup|- LTV/CAC ratio (target: > 3x)
M|lean-startup|- Payback period (how long to recoup CAC)
M|lean-startup|**Examples:** E-commerce, traditional businesses
M|lean-startup|**str:** Optimize until each customer generates enough profit to acquire more customers.
M|lean-startup|**Warning:** Don't use multiple engines simultaneously. Pick one, optimize it, then consider adding others.
M|lean-startup|See: [references/growth-engines.md](references/growth-engines.md) for engine selection and optimization.
M|lean-startup|**Purpose:** Root cause analysis to prevent problems from recurring.
M|lean-startup|**Process:**
M|lean-startup|1. A problem occurs (bug, outage, customer complaint)
M|lean-startup|2. Ask "Why did this happen?" → Answer
M|lean-startup|3. Ask "Why?" about that answer → Second answer
M|lean-startup|4. Repeat 5 times until you reach the root cause
M|lean-startup|5. Make proportional investments at each level
M|lean-startup|**Example:**
M|lean-startup|**Problem:** Website went down
M|lean-startup|1. **Why?** Server ran out of mem
M|lean-startup|2. **Why?** mem leak in new feature
M|lean-startup|3. **Why?** Code wasn't rv for mem management
M|lean-startup|4. **Why?** No code rv process for infrastructure changes
M|lean-startup|5. **Why?** Team is moving too fast to create processes
M|lean-startup|**Proportional investments:**
M|lean-startup|- Fix the immediate bug (level 1)
M|lean-startup|- Add mem monitoring (level 2)
M|lean-startup|- Implement code rv (level 3-4)
M|lean-startup|- Slow down to build quality processes (level 5)
M|lean-startup|**Anti-pattern:** Stop at level 1 (just fix the symptom).
M|lean-startup|See: [references/five-whys.md](references/five-whys.md) for facilitation guides.
M|lean-startup|**Principle:** Work in small batches to accelerate learning and reduce waste.
M|lean-startup|**Why small batches win:**
M|lean-startup|- Faster feedback loops
M|lean-startup|- Easier to pivot
M|lean-startup|- Less waste when you're wrong
M|lean-startup|- Faster time to market
M|lean-startup|**Examples:**
M|lean-startup|| Large Batch | Small Batch |
M|lean-startup||-------------|-------------|
M|lean-startup|| Build entire product, then launch | Launch landing page, then build |
M|lean-startup|| Release quarterly | Release weekly or daily |
M|lean-startup|| Plan 12-month roadmap | Plan 6-week cycles |
M|lean-startup|| Big bang rewrite | Incremental refactoring |
M|lean-startup|**Continuous dpl:** The ultimate small batch = deploy every code commit.
M|lean-startup|**Benefits:**
M|lean-startup|- Bugs are caught immediately
M|lean-startup|- Learning happens continuously
M|lean-startup|- Reduced risk per dpl
M|lean-startup|See: [references/small-batches.md](references/small-batches.md) for implementation patterns.
M|lean-startup|**For different contexts:**
M|lean-startup|1. **Smoke test:** Landing page + email list (validate demand)
M|lean-startup|2. **Concierge MVP:** Manually deliver service to 10 customers (validate value)
M|lean-startup|3. **Single-feature MVP:** Build one core workflow (validate engagement)
M|lean-startup|4. **Measure:** Retention, NPS, feature usage
M|lean-startup|5. **Pivot or scale:** Based on cohort data
M|lean-startup|1. **Innovation accounting:** Separate metrics from core business
M|lean-startup|2. **Protected teams:** Shield from quarterly revenue pressure
M|lean-startup|3. **Metered funding:** Unlock funding based on validated learning milestones
M|lean-startup|4. **Internal entrepreneurship:** Treat team as startup within company
M|lean-startup|1. **Feature flags:** Deploy behind flag, test with small cohort
M|lean-startup|2. **A/B test:** Measure impact on core metrics
M|lean-startup|3. **Kill, iterate, or scale:** Based on data
M|lean-startup|See: [references/applications.md](references/applications.md) for ctx-specific guides.
M|lean-startup|| Mistake | Why It Fails | Fix |
M|lean-startup||---------|-------------|------|
M|lean-startup|| **Building too much** | Waste before validation | Test with smoke test or concierge first |
M|lean-startup|| **Asking customers** | People don't know/mispredict | Observe behavior, not opinions |
M|lean-startup|| **Vanity metrics** | Feel-good numbers, no decisions | Track cohorts, conversion, retention |
M|lean-startup|| **No hypothesis** | Can't learn if you don't predict | Write hypothesis before each experiment |
M|lean-startup|| **Pivot too slow** | Waste runway | Set clear pivot criteria upfront |
M|lean-startup|| **Skip innovation accounting** | Can't tell if you're improving | Establish baseline, measure tuning efforts |
M|lean-startup|Audit any product dev plan:
M|lean-startup|| Question | If No | Action |
M|lean-startup||----------|-------|--------|
M|lean-startup|| What's the riskiest assumption? | You're building on shaky ground | Map leap-of-faith assumptions |
M|lean-startup|| How will you test it? | You're guessing | Design MVP to test assumption |
M|lean-startup|| What metric will validate/invalidate? | You won't learn | Define actionable metrics |
M|lean-startup|| Can you test with less than this? | You're over-building | Shrink MVP further |
M|lean-startup|| What will you do if the experiment fails? | No pivot criteria | Define pivot triggers upfront |
M|lean-startup|**Phase 1: Problem/Solution Fit**
M|lean-startup|- **Goal:** Validate the problem exists and customers care
M|lean-startup|- **Method:** Customer discovery, smoke tests, concierge MVP
M|lean-startup|- **Metric:** Customers willing to pay or commit
M|lean-startup|**Phase 2: Product/Market Fit**
M|lean-startup|- **Goal:** Build something people want
M|lean-startup|- **Method:** Build MVP, iterate based on usage data
M|lean-startup|- **Metric:** High retention, organic growth, strong engagement
M|lean-startup|**Phase 3: Scale**
M|lean-startup|- **Goal:** Grow efficiently
M|lean-startup|- **Method:** Optimize growth engine, improve unit economics
M|lean-startup|- **Metric:** Sustainable, profitable growth
M|lean-startup|**Anti-pattern:** Skipping Phase 1-2 and jumping straight to scale.
